.TH _printf 3 "May 2026" "Holberton School" "_printf man-page"

.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include <main.h>
.PP
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function produces output according to a format string and writes
the result to stdout (standard output stream).
.PP
The format string is composed of zero or more directives: ordinary characters
(not %), which are copied unchanged to the output, and conversion
specifications, each of which results in fetching zero or more subsequent
arguments.
.PP
Each conversion specification is introduced by the character
.B %
and ends with a conversion specifier.
.PP
If an unknown conversion specifier is encountered, the '%' character
is printed followed by the unknown specifier.
.PP
The
.B _printf()
function returns the number of characters printed.
.PP
If format is NULL, or if a '%' appears at the end of the format string with no following character, the function returns -1.

.PP
Output is buffered using an internal static buffer. Characters are
stored and written to stdout when the buffer is full or when a flush
operation is triggered.

.SH CONVERSION SPECIFIERS
.TP
.B c
Prints a single character. The int argument is converted to an unsigned char.

.TP
.B s
Prints a string of characters. The argument is expected to be a pointer
to an array of characters (char *). Characters are printed up to the
null byte.

.TP
.B d
.B i
Prints a signed decimal integer. The int argument is converted to
signed decimal notation.

.TP
.B %
Prints a literal percent sign. No argument is converted.

.TP
.B b
Prints an unsigned integer in binary notation. The unsigned int argument is converted to
base 2 representation and printed as a sequence of '0' and '1' characters.

.TP
.B u
Prints an unsigned decimal integer. The unsigned int argument is converted to
base 10 notation.

.TP
.B o
Prints an unsigned integer in octal notation. The unsigned int argument is
converted to base 8 representation.

.TP
.B x
Prints an unsigned integer in lowercase hexadecimal notation. The unsigned int
argument is converted to base 16 using digits 0–9 and a–f.

.TP
.B X
Prints an unsigned integer in uppercase hexadecimal notation. The unsigned int
argument is converted to base 16 using digits 0–9 and A–F.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success,
.B _printf()
returns the number of characters printed, excluding the null byte
used to end output to strings.
Returns -1 if format is NULL or if the format string ends with a bare '%'.

.SH NOTES
The following features of the standard printf are not supported:
.PP
.RS
- Flag characters (0, -, +, space, #)
.RE
.RS
- Field width
.RE
.RS
- Precision
.RE
.RS
- Length modifiers (h, l, ll, etc.)
.RE

.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Print a simple string:
.PP
.RS
_printf("Hello, World!\n");
.RE

.PP
Print a character:
.PP
.RS
_printf("Character: %c\n", 'A');
.RE

.PP
Print a string:
.PP
.RS
_printf("String: %s\n", "Holberton");
.RE

.PP
Print an integer:
.PP
.RS
_printf("Integer: %d\n", 42);
.RE

.PP
Print a negative integer:
.PP
.RS
_printf("Negative: %d\n", -762534);
.RE

.PP
Print a percent sign:
.PP
.RS
_printf("Percent: %%\n");
.RE

.PP
Print a binary number:
.PP
.RS
_printf("Binary: %b\n", 5);
.RE

.PP
Print an unsigned decimal number:
.PP
.RS
_printf("Unsigned decimal: %u\n", 30);
.RE

.PP
Print an unsigned octal number:
.PP
.RS
_printf("Unsigned octal: %o\n", 100);
.RE

.PP
Print unsigned hexadecimal in lowercase:
.PP
.RS
_printf("Unsigned hexadecimal: %x\n", 255);
.RE

.PP
Print unsigned hexadecimal in uppercase:
.PP
.RS
_printf("Unsigned hexadecimal: %X\n", 255);
.RE

